  "prompt": "Which day can be the first and the last day of a century?",
  "response": "In the Gregorian calendar, the first day of a century (January 1) and the last day of a century (December 31) can fall on any day of the week. This variability is due to the way leap years are accounted for and how they influence the progression of weekdays over a 100-year period.\n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Leap Years and Century Years:**\n   - **Regular Years:** Have 365 days.\n   - **Leap Years:** Occur every 4 years, adding an extra day (366 days).\n   - **Century Years:** Years divisible by 100 are **not** leap years unless they are also divisible by 400. For example, the year 2000 was a leap year, but 1900 was not.\n\n2. **Day Progression Over a Century:**\n   - A century typically has **24** leap years (if not divisible by 400) or **25** leap years (if divisible by 400).\n   - This results in a total of **36,524** days (for 24 leap years) or **36,525** days (for 25 leap years) in a century.\n   - When you divide these totals by 7 (the number of days in a week), you'll find that:\n     - **36,524 days \u2261 5 mod 7**\n     - **36,525 days \u2261 6 mod 7**\n   - This means that the day of the week advances by either **5** or **6** days over a century.\n\n3. **Implications for January 1 and December 31:**\n   - Because of the above day progression, **January 1** of a new century can start on any day of the week.\n   - Similarly, **December 31** of a century can also fall on any day of the week, depending on the specific century in question.\n\n### Examples:\n\n- **January 1, 2001:** Was a Monday.\n- **December 31, 2000:** Was a Sunday.\n\nThis variability ensures that over different centuries, the starting and ending days shift across the days of the week.\n\n### Conclusion:\n\n**Any day of the week is possible for both the first day (January\u202f1) and the last day (December\u202f31) of a century.**",
